JUDITH Masalela (46) says she can&rsquo;t sleep at night . . . because her ancestors won&rsquo;t leave her alone.&ldquo;They keep on sneaking into my bed, grabbing me by my pyjamas and demanding that I divorce my husband,&rdquo; she claimed.&ldquo;The ancestors ask me why am I still using my husband&rsquo;s surname. &ldquo;They sometimes klap me.&rdquo; Judith said her ancestors were angry because her husband left her with two kids in their rented house in Olievenhoutbosch, Midrand, Gauteng.&ldquo;I have tried to do rituals and burn impepho, and to explain to them that it&rsquo;s not my fault that the divorce process has been delayed,&rdquo; she told Daily Sun.Judith said she got married to her husband, Richard Masalela (52) in 2005 but in 2012, he got a job as a security guard and a year later, moved out of the house. &ldquo;I heard that he has a girlfriend. &ldquo;Why can&rsquo;t he just take his surname back and get out of my life?&rdquo;Judith showed Daily Sun the copy of a receipt from the Kempton Park Magistrates Court, which she paid to have her husband summonsed to appear in court to get a divorce.But the sheriff of the court has not been able to get Richard to come to court.Judith said she has a boyfriend whom she wanted to marry.Richard admitted Judith was his wife. &ldquo;Whatever she told you is the truth,&rdquo; Richard told the People&rsquo;s Paper.